thods. Still, the result was politically potent. As Mukerji shows, the project took land and power from local nobles, using water itself as a silent agent of the state to disrupt traditions of local life that had served regional elites.Impossible Engineering opens a surprising window into the world of seventeenth-century France and illuminates a singular work of engineering undertaken to empower the state through technical conquest of nature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 7aTechnology & Engineering / History.2bisacsh  aAppointee.  aBenedict Anderson.  aBernard Palissy.  aBook.  aBountiful Harvest.  aBruno Latour.  aC. Wright Mills.  aCalculation.  aCambridge University Press.  aCanal du Midi.  aCarcassonne.  aCardinal Mazarin.  aChartism.  aChauvinism.  aCivil engineer.  aCivil engineering.  aClassical tradition.  aColonialism.  aContentious politics.  aCourtesy.  aDe re metallica.  aDiscipline and Punish.  aDivine right of kings.  aDrug court.  aEminent domain.  aEngineer.  aEngineering design process.  aEngineering.  aExperiential knowledge.  aFernand Braudel.  aFor the Glory.  aFratricide.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aGod's Grace.  aGovernance.  aGovernmentality.  aHandbook.  aHomeschooling.  aHuguenot.  aHydraulic engineering.  aImmanuel Wallerstein.  aInception.  aIntendant.  aJean Bodin.  aLaborer.  aLanguedoc.  aLocal Hero.  aLogistics.  aLou Henry Hoover.  aLuc Boltanski.  aMalpas Tunnel.  aMarin Mersenne.  aMarket town.  aMetallurgy.  aMuseum.  aNeoliberalism.  aNicolas Fouquet.  aNoel Malcolm.  aPierre Bourdieu.  aPolitical alliance.  aPolitics.  aPolitique.  aPosthumanism.  aPozzolana.  aPrecedent.  aPresses Universitaires de France.  aRevolution.  aRoman Empire.  aRoman aqued